title: Budgeting 101: The 50/30/20 Rule
text: A popular budgeting framework is the 50/30/20 rule. Allocate 50% of your post-tax income to Needs (rent, groceries, basic utilities), 30% to Wants (dining out, entertainment, shopping), and 20% to Savings and Debt Repayment (SIPs, emergency fund, loan EMIs). In India, where rent in metros can be high, you might adjust this to 60/20/20, but the principle remains: pay yourself (save) before you spend on luxuries.

title: Why You Need an Emergency Fund
text: An emergency fund is money kept aside for unforeseen expenses like job loss or medical emergencies. It should cover 3-6 months of your expenses (not income). Keep this in liquid assets like a high-yield savings account or a Liquid Mutual Fund, not in stocks or locked-in FDs, so you can access it instantly without penalty.

title: Debt Repayment Strategies: Snowball vs Avalanche
text: Two main strategies exist for paying off debt. 1. Debt Snowball: Pay minimums on all loans, but put extra money towards the smallest loan first. The psychological win of closing a loan motivates you. 2. Debt Avalanche: Pay off the loan with the highest interest rate first (e.g., credit card debt at 30-40%). This saves you the most money mathematically. In India, always prioritize high-interest debt like personal loans and credit cards over low-interest ones like home loans, which also offer tax benefits.

title: Introduction to Mutual Funds and SIPs
text: A Mutual Fund pools money from many investors to invest in stocks, bonds, or other assets. For most beginners, an Index Fund (like Nifty 50) is a safe starting point. A Systematic Investment Plan (SIP) allows you to invest small amounts (e.g., 500) regularly. This instills discipline and helps in rupee-cost averaging, reducing the risk of market volatility over time.

title: Asset Allocation and Risk Profile
text: Don't put all your eggs in one basket. Asset allocation means dividing your portfolio among different asset classes: Equity (Stocks/Mutual Funds) for growth, Debt (PPF, EPF, Bonds) for stability, and Gold/Real Estate for hedging. A common rule of thumb for equity exposure is '100 minus your age'. If you are 25, you might have 75% in equity. However, this depends on your risk appetite and financial goals.

title: Tax Saving Instruments in India
text: Under Section 80C of the Income Tax Act, you can claim deductions up to 1.5 Lakh. Common options include: 1. EPF (Employee Provident Fund): Debt instrument, safe, long-term. 2. PPF (Public Provident Fund): 15-year lock-in, tax-free interest. 3. ELSS (Equity Linked Savings Scheme): Mutual funds with a 3-year lock-in, good for wealth creation. 4. Life Insurance Premiums (Term Insurance is best). Choose based on your liquidity needs and risk profile.

title: Rule Number One
text: Rule No. 1: Never lose money. Rule No. 2: Never forget Rule No. 1. The stock market is a device for transferring money from the impatient to the patient. We simply attempt to be fearful when others are greedy and to be greedy only when others are fearful.

title: Economic Moats
text: The most important thing to look for in a business is a durable competitive advantage, or an 'economic moat'. This could be a brand, a patent, or a network effect that protects the business from competitors. We look for castles with wide moats around them, managed by honest and able lords.

title: Circle of Competence
text: You don't have to be an expert on every company, or even many. You only have to be able to evaluate companies within your circle of competence. The size of that circle is not very important; knowing its boundaries, however, is vital. Stick to what you know and understand.

title: Voting Machine vs Weighing Machine
text: In the short run, the market is a voting machine - acting on popularity and emotion. In the long run, it is a weighing machine - measuring the true substance of a business. Ignore short-term noise.

title: Index Funds
text: For the average investor, the best strategy is to buy a low-cost S&P 500 index fund and hold it forever. Don't try to pick individual stocks unless you are willing to make it your full-time job. Bet on American business.

title: Price vs Value
text: Price is what you pay. Value is what you get. It's far better to buy a wonderful company at a fair price than a fair company at a wonderful price.

title: Long Term Horizon
text: Our favorite holding period is forever. If you aren't willing to own a stock for ten years, don't even think about owning it for ten minutes. Time is the friend of the wonderful company, the enemy of the mediocre.

title: Derivatives
text: Derivatives are financial weapons of mass destruction. They add massive complexity and hidden leverage to the system. Stay away from things you don't understand.

title: Reputation
text: It takes 20 years to build a reputation and five minutes to ruin it. If you think about that, you'll do things differently. Lose money for the firm, and I will be understanding; lose a shred of reputation for the firm, and I will be ruthless.

title: Cash Holdings
text: We always keep enough cash around so I feel very comfortable. I never want to be dependent on the kindness of strangers. Cash is oxygen; you don't notice it when it's there, but it's the only thing that matters when it's gone.

title: Wealth Creation
text: Seek wealth, not money or status. Wealth is having assets that earn while you sleep. Money is how we transfer time and wealth. Status is your place in the social hierarchy. Ignore status games; they are zero-sum. Wealth creation is positive-sum.

title: Leverage
text: Fortunes require leverage. Business leverage comes from capital, people, and products with no marginal cost of replication (code and media). Code and media are the leverage behind the newly rich. You can create software and media that works for you while you sleep.

title: Specific Knowledge
text: Specific knowledge is knowledge that you cannot be trained for. If society can train you, it can train someone else, and replace you. Specific knowledge is found by pursuing your genuine curiosity and passion rather than whatever is hot right now. Building specific knowledge will feel like play to you but looked like work to others.

title: Equity Ownership
text: You will not get rich renting out your time. You must own equity - a piece of a business - to gain your financial freedom. This is the only way to decouple your inputs from your outputs.

title: Compound Interest
text: All the benefits in life come from compound interest - money, relationships, and knowledge. Play long-term games with long-term people. 99% of effort is wasted. You have to be right only once.

title: Happiness and Wealth
text: Happiness is a choice and a skill. It is not the outcome of wealth. Wealth buys freedom, but it doesn't buy peace. Peace is happiness at rest. Happiness is peace in motion.

title: Reading
text: Read what you love until you love to read. The foundation of learning is reading. It is better to read a great book 10 times than 10 mediocre books once. Understand the basics of microeconomics, game theory, psychology, and persuasion.

title: Judgment
text: In an age of leverage, one correct decision can win everything. Judgment is the ability to make the right decision with incomplete information. Wisdom is judgment without the anxiety.

title: Patience
text: Impatience with actions, patience with results. The world is an efficient market; if something was easy, everyone would do it. Anything worth doing takes time.

title: Accountability
text: Embrace accountability and take business risks under your own name. Society will reward you with responsibility, equity, and leverage. The most accountable people are the ones who get the most leverage.

title: The Economic Machine
text: The economy is like a simple machine but many people don't understand it. It consists of a few simple parts and a lot of simple transactions that satisfy human nature. These transactions are driven by three main forces: productivity growth, the short-term debt cycle, and the long-term debt cycle.

title: Radical Truth and Transparency
text: To be successful, you must embrace reality and deal with it. Pain + Reflection = Progress. Radical truth and radical transparency are essential for meaningful work and meaningful relationships. You need to be open-minded and willing to be wrong. The goal is to find the best answer, not just the one you came up with.

title: The Holy Grail of Investing
text: Diversification is the holy grail of investing. By combining uncorrelated return streams, you can reduce your risk without reducing your expected return. This is how you structure a portfolio that can withstand any economic season (All Weather Portfolio). Do not bet on a single outcome; bet on the balance.

title: Debt Cycles
text: Credit is the most important part of the economy. It allows spending to increase faster than income (short-term debt cycle). Eventually, debts become too large relative to income (long-term debt cycle), leading to deleveraging. Understanding where we are in the cycle is key.

title: The Pain Button
text: When you encounter pain, it is a signal that you have run into reality. Instead of reacting emotionally, view it as a puzzle to solve. Push the 'Pain Button' to reflect. Pain + Reflection = Progress.

title: Idea Meritocracy
text: The best organizations are idea meritocracies, where the best ideas win regardless of who they come from. To achieve this, you need radical candor and a system for believability-weighted decision making.

title: Evolution
text: Evolution is the single greatest force in the universe; it is the only thing that is permanent and it drives everything. Evolve or die. Your goal is to evolve and contribute to evolution.

title: 5-Step Process
text: 1. Have clear goals. 2. Identify and don't tolerate the problems standing in your way. 3. Diagnose the problems to get at their root causes. 4. Design a plan to eliminate the problems. 5. Push through to completion.

title: Cash is Trash
text: In an inflationary environment with money printing, cash is trash. It loses value over time. You want to be in a diversified mix of assets - stocks, gold, commodities - that will appreciate or hold value.

title: Currency Devaluation
text: When governments have too much debt, they print money. This devalues the currency. While nominal asset prices might rise, the real buying power of cash falls. History shows this happens repeatedly.
